observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Municipality establish an inventory management system on receipt, distribution and/ or utilization of in-kind donations for proper monitoring to safeguard these inventories.
Henceforth, officials and/ or personnel concerned on related transactions adhere to COA Circular No. 2014-002 as amended by COA Circular No. 2020-009, viz:
Prepare issuance for in-kind donations issued and require the departments responsible for the distribution of relief goods and other supplies to submit Proof of Receipt by and Distribution to the Beneficiaries/ end-users;
Prepare Summary/ List of Donations Received, Distributed and Balances every month or every quarter supported by Acknowledgment Receipts, Proof of Receipt by and Distribution to the Beneficiaries/ end-users, and Inventory of Remaining Balances and submit the same to the NDRRMC through the OCD, copy furnish the Audit Team within ten (10) working days after the end of each month or quarter;
Maintain Stock Cards/ Property Card for all donations in-kind received and update regularly;
Maintain Registry of Donated Relief Goods for each kind of inventory items;
Prepare Property Acknowledgment Receipt (PAR) for issuance of donated PPEs andInventory Custodian Slip (ICS) for the issuances of tangible items which costs P15,000.00 or less with a life of more than a year and are not considered as PPE, to establish accountability over them and furnish the Municipal Accountant with the PAR and ICS; and
Summarize the data from the documents obtained, compare records with Registry of Donated Relief Goods maintained by the Supply Office or by the designated MSWDOfficer for check and balance, and accordingly disclose all necessary information in the Notes to the Financial Statements.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the Municipal Treasurer to:
Secure from the GSIS General Insurance Fund (GIF), insurances covering properties, contracts, rights of action, and other insurable risks of the LGU;
Prepare the Property Inventory Form (PIF) of all the insurable properties and other assets, showing their latest appraised values/valuation, appraisal date, location, and other information;
Extract from the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment, as well as from the Report on the Physical Count of Inventories, prepared in accordance with the prevailing guidelines, the data for the PIF pertaining to the insurable assets and interest of the government (excluding impaired properties for disposal);
Cause the appraisal of the insurable properties and other assets of the LGU.  For this purpose, an in-house appraisal shall be sufficient if the property or insurable interest has a value of P10 million and below.  Otherwise, an independent appraisal shall be necessary;
Submit the consolidated PIF to the Audit Team and the GIF, GSIS, not later than April 30 of each year; and
Include in the annual budget the amount of premiums for the general insurance covering all insurable properties and other assets and ensure its payment to the GSIS.

4. implement immediately the projects in accordance with the timeframe provided for in the MOA to return to the Source Agency maximize the beneficial use of the government projects/program and the eventual return of unused funds, if any;
5. prepare the corresponding reports for each of the completed projects and submit the same to the Accountant within one month from completion; and
6. report to the LCE any project/program which cannot be immediately implemented for proper disposition or referral to the Source Agency.
We also recommended that the Municipal Accountant:
7. prepare the Disbursement Voucher to initiate the return of the unused/ unexpended funds or remaining balances and forward the same to the Municipal Treasurer for issuance of checks and remittance to the Bureau of Treasury;
8. submit the Fund Utilization Report on completed projects to the concerned Source Agency including the check on the return of balances, to effect its proper and full liquidation.

